Spectacular wingsuit jump over Bogota
Athlete Jonathan Florez jumped from a helicopter over Bogota, the capital of Colombia, on Thursday.
Armed with a wingsuit, he flew at 100 miles [160 km] an hour over the famous sanctuary of Monserrate, at an altitude of over 3,000 meters, where many onlookers had gathered to watch his feat.
A black box in your car?
While road planners in the United States are struggling to find the money to repair dilapidated highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that is attached to the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record every mile driven by a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and government offices to revamp the outdated system of funding major U.S. highways.
The generally uninteresting sector of highway planning has suddenly provoked a lively debate and heated alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to lobby for the government to use the little boxes to keep track of the miles you drive, and possibly the road you drive, and then use the information to write a tax bill.
The Tea Party is terrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about privacy protection.
And while members of Congress can't agree on whether to proceed, several states haven't waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they can move to a system where drivers pay based on the number of miles driven.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS tracking system, on a test drive.
This is truly essential for our nation.
 It's not like we have a choice, said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which expects the state to start recording the miles driven by every California motorist by 2025.
There's going to be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially strapped.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can go more than a mile with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax even by a cent when gasoline prices are high.
 The gas tax is simply not sustainable, said Lee Munnich, a transport policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracking devices on 500 cars to test a mileage payment system.
 This is proving to be the most logical alternative in the long term, he said.
Wonks calls it a mileage charge.
The idea is not surprisingly appealing to city liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits in ways that reduce congestion and emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to meet the goals set out in the state's ambitious global warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market advocates at the Reason Foundation also welcome the idea of charging drivers per mile.
 This is not just a tax going into a big black hole, said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. Transportation Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go down the pay-per-mile path.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
But the House floor killed the proposal, responding to concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who must travel many miles each day to get to work or to town.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are making progress.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the nation's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon be paying the state mileage instead of gas tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is conducting a test run on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently fitted their cars with a tracking device, drivers were concerned that the government might be tracking their every move.
 Worries about Big Brother and stuff like that are a big problem, said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the trial, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website:  It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices. 
There is no need to build a huge, bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily comings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states that is now scrambling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car has driven, but not the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Research into this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up called True Mileage.
The company was not originally intended to help motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It was looking to break into the emerging market of car insurance, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she is testing have been popular with highway planners because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically uploaded by modem.
 People will be more likely to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them, said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been serious errors in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less expensive and far less intrusive methods of doing this.
In Oregon, planners are trying the experiment by offering drivers a variety of options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a flat rate based on the average number of miles driven by all residents in the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxing system that would also be equipped to pay for parking, provide insurance  pay-to-drive  and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
 Drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them, said a paper on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole debate about paying per mile is simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply handle the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising gasoline taxes.
A one-off or annual additional tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much petrol, so that everyone pays his fair share.
 There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin, said Randy Rentschler, the committee's director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do this, hundreds of millions of motorists will have to worry about their privacy and a bunch of other things.
David Bowie: four new songs to listen to
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, which was released in January, he has devised a deluxe reissue scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already surfaced on the Web.
The announcement of the release of a new David Bowie album had left everyone stunned.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he announced that a new album would be released in March.
After a decade of silence (the last album, Reality, was released in 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that he could still be counted on to make the pop scene sparkle.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one trick in his bag with The Next Day.
Thin White Duke planned to re-release the album on November 4.
He's prepared a feast for his fans.
The reissue, titled The Next Day Extra, will be released as a three-disc set: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four music videos already released.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks from the original album: the three tracks from the Deluxe Edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie has actually made a video presentation of this beautiful box.
He introduces not only each of the records, but also the accessories that came with them: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, most importantly, it gives a taste of his new title Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and a skillfully mastered rock electricity.
The first ever
But Atomica isn't the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available online.
The Informer is a double-sided, eerie intro before a light ride that gradually slows to make way for a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John's Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems to be in his element when he's not on the ground anymore.
Space Oddity, on the other hand, was a lot worse.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: could he be from another planet?
The guitar riffs, the bewitching, make you want to leave Earth.
Bowie is having fun playing the chameleon with these titles: turn-by-turn informant, man on a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals at the same time, playing on different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in his hand in the photo of the Louis Vuitton campaign, Invitation to Travel, of which he is the new face.
He will be featured in one of their commercials, which will air starting November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that wounded soldiers were not being released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Nicholson said that before their release, the soldiers were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
He said all wounded soldiers were receiving appropriate treatment for their return to civilian life and none were released until they were ready.
Critics accuse the government of trying to save money by not allowing wounded soldiers - who do not meet the army's "universal service" rule requiring staff to be able to perform a range of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
They cited two cases reported by the Canadian Press, including one soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, with post-traumatic stress disorder, was released from the Army despite his request to stay on for one more year so that he could receive a fully indexed pension.
His case comes after Corporal Glen Kirkland testified before a parliamentary committee last month that he was pushed out before he was ready because he didn't meet the universal service rule.
Mr Hawkins pointed out that a soldier can be prepared to leave with plans and consultations, but that this is totally different from wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready", he told The Canadian Press on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was any way I could stay, and they said no.
Since the start of major fighting in Afghanistan, the military has struggled to determine how much leeway it can give wounded soldiers who want to stay in the ranks but are unfit for combat.
Under current rules, seriously wounded soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for deployment overseas, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year show that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the service age required to receive retirement benefits.
Liberal Veterans Affairs spokesman Jim Karygiannis called on Wednesday for the reinstatement of Corporal Hawkins, while New Democrat Jack Harris called for an immediate end to "this shameful practice".
Disney is going to launch an animated series on tablets
The American media and entertainment group Disney has decided to give preference to tablets over its own television channels for the forthcoming release of a new children's series.
The first nine episodes of Sheriff Callie's Wild West will be available starting November 24th on watchdisneyjunior.com or through its mobile and tablet app.
The worldwide launch on Disney Group channels is not planned until 2014, the statement from its Disney Junior division details.
The cartoon, aimed at children aged 2 to 7, tells the adventures of Callie, a cat who is the sheriff of a town in the American West where she keeps order with a magic lasso.
Each episode consists of two 11-minute stories.
"Interacting with smartphones and tablets is second nature for kids today", said Albert Cheng, vice president of digital products at Disney/ABC Television Group, as quoted in the release.
This type of experience is part of Disney's efforts to "extend the lifespan of its series and build new relationships with its audience through digital platforms that are becoming increasingly important", he added.
A survey published earlier this week by Common Sense Media showed an explosion in the use of mobile devices by young children in the United States: 38% of those under 2 years of age have already used a tablet or phone, and 72% of those under 8 years of age, compared to 10% and 38% respectively two years ago.
Snowden is willing to  cooperate  with Germany on the issue of US surveillance
Edward Snowden, the whistleblower for the US intelligence services, said he was willing to travel to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the US National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander did not provide answers about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he has asylum rights, to discuss his testimony in Germany.
In a letter the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, Mr Snowden said:  Although the result of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat differences of opinion as a leak and seeks to penalize political discourse with charges against which it is impossible to defend itself. 
However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Mr. Snowden wrote that he believed that international support could persuade the U.S. government to drop criminal charges against him.
As part of the lawsuit filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is charged with espionage and theft of government property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, German Interior Minister, told Zeit Online:  If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will make it possible. 
Relations between the United States and Germany have been strained following complaints that the NSA had tapped the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Oppermann, the MP who heads the parliamentary group overseeing foreign intelligence, said that if there was a chance to hear Mr Snowden as a witness  without putting him in danger and completely ruining relations with the US, it was worth taking.
Mr. Ströbele, a German Green MP, posted a picture of himself with Mr. Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr Ströbele said that according to the lawyer for the former NSA consultant, Mr Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Mr Snowden were to testify in Germany, he should be assured that he would be in safety there, the MEP said.
Mr Snowden wrote in his letter that he had been the subject of a campaign of persecution  serious and sustained  which had forced him to leave his country.
However, he said he was encouraged by the worldwide reaction to  my act of political expression .
Citizens around the world and senior officials  including in the United States  felt that the disclosure of an inexplicable system of permanent surveillance was in the public interest.
The letter offers cooperation with the German authorities  once the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved .
Cogeco Cable could soon offer interactive TV
Cogeco Cable subscribers may well be able to access apps like Facebook, Twitter and ultimately the on-demand video service Netflix via their TV in the not-so-distant future.
Cogeco's subsidiary said on Thursday that it was conducting preliminary testing of the beta version of the platform with some of its users.
"This will allow us to showcase more user-friendly interfaces and more options", explained Cogeco's President and CEO, Louis Audet, in an interview.
Cogeco Cable is thus following in the footsteps of its competitors, such as Bell, although the Cogeco subsidiary has not yet set a specific date for this new platform.
"You have to adapt and change or resist change and fail", Audet stressed.
The ultimate goal remains to offer tools that our customers currently do not have access to.
Telecom giant Rogers has already indicated that it could offer Netflix if certain technical details, which have not been mentioned, could be worked out.
In the United States, the popular video service says it is in talks with some major cable companies to make its service available through their broadcast platforms.
The CEO of Cogeco and Cogeco Cable also welcomed the announcement made by the Harper government during its Speech from the Throne on 16 October.
Ottawa wants to force cable and satellite providers to offer customers the option of paying for card services.
"For about two and a half years we have been saying that the idea of forcing consumers to buy large packages of chains is not working", said Audet.
He hopes, however, that the consultations conducted by the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Council (CRTC) will lead to interesting recommendations.
"These discussions will have to produce a new kind of framework for defining our new Canadian cultural policy on television", said Cogeco's CEO.
The CRTC has been conducting public consultations since last week and they are expected to continue with industry next spring.
On the earnings side, Cogeco reported a net profit of 43.8 million in the fourth quarter, or 82¢ per share.
This is down from net profit of 44.9 million, or 83¢ per share, in the same period last year.
The Montreal-based company attributes this decline to depreciation costs related to new acquisitions.
Cogeco acquired US-based cable distributor Atlantic Broadband in 2012 for EUR 1.36 billion.
This was the company's first major acquisition after the failed one in Portugal.
Last December, the Montreal-based company also bought Peer 1 Network Enterprises, a Vancouver-based Internet provider, for $526 million.
As for Cogeco's revenues, they increased by 41.5% in the fourth quarter to 504.7 million.
The Commission has already decided to grant a loan of ECU 1.8 billion for the current financial year.
Net profit for its main subsidiary, Cogeco Cable, was 43.9 million, or 90¢ per share, down from 45.7 million, or 93¢ per share, in the same period last year.
However, Cogeco Cable's revenues increased by 45% to 470.4 million.
The company lost 15,237 customers in the fourth quarter.
However, for the financial year 2013, the number of Cogeco Cable customers is up to 5546.
Mr. Audet is not concerned about the number of customers fluctuating like that.
I do not think this is a sign of a change in trend, he said.
It varies from quarter to quarter with very intense competition.
Horse in beef products
Horse meat has been found in cans of beef products sold by two small British retailers, the Food Safety Authority said today.
Routine tests revealed that the products, which were manufactured in January in Romania and sold by Home Bargains and Quality Save, contained between 1 and 5 per cent horse DNA.
"Since horse meat is not mentioned in the list of ingredients, it should not have been in the product", the agency said.
A scandal over the presence of horse meat in cooked dishes broke out in Europe earlier this year following tests in Ireland.
According to the European Commission's reviews, France was the country most affected by the presence of this type of meat in products that were supposed to contain only beef.
