Frontier Airlines is considering charging for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines is planning to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although in its announcement on Wednesday, it said passengers could take the unopened can with them when they land.
The new carry-on baggage charge applies to bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fees were paid in advance and $100 if travelers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 bill was meant to encourage travelers to pay the fare in advance.
 We don't want to charge this price, she explained.
Airlines started charging for first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges put as much as they could into the hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no more room in these compartments.
These charges are a way of ensuring that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said that these new fees won't really be used to raise money.
This is to make Frontier's most loyal customers understand that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the upper compartments.
Passengers who buy their tickets on the airline's website will not have to pay.
For example, a passenger queuing at a Border boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in line might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and check-in procedures are changing to ensure passengers know about these charges before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier's hand luggage charges won't be enforced until the summer, though no date has been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They consider that the costs of handling baggage are high and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines are charging enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
Yet many of them did not have to pay for luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. first applied hand luggage charges three years ago, and low-cost carrier Allegiant followed a little later.
The only other airline that charges such fees is Hungary's Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the extra fees.
He estimated, in a December 2011 report, that Spirit's hand luggage costs brought in $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently traveled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the boarding gate when passengers learned of the company's unusual hand luggage charges.
 I have never seen such a smooth boarding procedure in my entire professional career , he said.
I expected to see a gnashing of teeth and a fight breaking out at the door.
The plane was full, he added,  the passengers boarded at lightning speed .
Frontier also does like Spirit and charges $2 for a coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier said passengers who drink soda or fruit juice can take the can with them unopened, and those who drink coffee can be served again free of charge.
She'll always give out free water.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008 but withdrew seven months later after passengers complained and when no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier's decision to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy their tickets directly from the airline is its latest effort to entice customers to go to its website.
Airlines pay online travel sellers like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This has prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of going to an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it started offering only half a mile of loyalty to customers who bought their tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut the mileage premium by 25% on a trip.
For example, a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased from an online travel agency would save 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they purchase their ticket directly from Frontier's website.
Frontier has a loyal clientele in her hometown of Denver, but her business is in decline and she's losing money.
Revenue fell 9 percent and its flight capacity declined almost 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to fix Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
The NSA blames an internal error, not hackers, for the crash of its website.
The shadow National Security Agency said Friday that it was a bug that caused its public website to go down for a few hours, not hackers as some had claimed online.
 NSA.gov was inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update , the intelligence agency said in an email statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
The allegations that the failure was due to a distributed denial of service (DDoS) attack are false.
Earlier tonight, online server trackers noted that the NSA website had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still can't access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson told ABC News that the agency's sensitive internal network was not compromised at all.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesman explained.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the NSA website crash by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
Cyber tactics are not very sophisticated and the attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the targeted system.
The formerly top secret NSA, once dubbed the  No Such Agency , has come under intense scrutiny and criticism in recent months following a wave of revelations about its extensive domestic and foreign communications surveillance programs  that are part of the NSA's classified files stolen from the agency and leaked by disillusioned former NSA consultant Edward Snowden.
The growing controversy surrounding the agency has led to much speculation that tonight's incident was the result of a targeted cyber operation.
Downtown Delta now closed
The Delta Hotel Centre-Ville closed its doors Thursday in Montreal after 36 years of operation.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to developers who are going to turn it into student housing.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have still not found new jobs.
Delta promises not to let its employees down.
Employers came to meet with employees directly on site, we met with employees individually to assess their needs.
"This support will continue for the next six months", explains Félix Bisson, regional director of labour relations at Delta Hotels.
The closure of Delta comes in a highly competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned that building had choices to make.
Either he was reinvesting in the building to continue operating it, so there was tens of millions of dollars of investment while the competition is very fierce, there are a lot of new hotels that have popped up in Montreal.
"Or he was selling it to someone else and that is what happened", says Paul Arsenault, chair of the Transat Tourism Chair at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
Other hotels in Montreal will also be converted in the coming months, such as Crown Plaza, which will be converted into a retirement home.
Meanwhile, four hotel projects totalling nearly 600 rooms will be built within two years.
Titan CEO says the Goodyear Amiens acquisition plan starts with zero employees
After throwing in the towel with a bang in January for the partial takeover of the Goodyear Amiens-Nord site promised to close, Maurice Taylor, CEO of the American tire manufacturer Titan, today said he was ready to save 333 jobs out of the 1,137 at the plant.
Arnaud Montebourg, the minister for productive recovery, had already announced this on Monday 21 October.
After giving up the plan to buy the factory in January, you're back today.
You have made violent attacks and insults, speaking of 'so-called workers' who 'work three hours a day', of 'crazy' unions, targeting the CGT.
We don't understand this turn of events.
Is it to please Mr. Montebourg ?
I'm not trying to please anyone.
Except for my wife.
Mr. Montebourg is a charming young man trying to save some of the highest-paying industrial jobs.
If I hurt anyone by what I said, I'm sorry.
But France has a high level of taxation and unemployment too.
Does the truth hurt you?
Working seven hours a day when in other countries you work eight hours is a handicap for France.
In India, China and many other countries, people work ten to twelve hours a day.
But I have no prejudice against France.
What I see is a factory that makes good farm tires, has good equipment, is well located and has room to expand.
Why does Titan need this factory so badly?
Titan doesn't need to buy this factory.
But with a fair price and skilled workers, it's worth a try.
What kind of agreement do you expect between the CGT and Goodyear?
If, since the announcement of the closure of the plant, Goodyear had offered employees a good severance package, I think 100% of the employees would have accepted it.
Now, let's say Titan buys the closed plant from Goodyear.
Titan could then move the machines to Poland or any other EU country that still has its own currency.
I think Mr. Montebourg knows that.
He wants to keep the Amiens factory with at least 333 well-paid jobs.
Titan agrees to recruit them from among Goodyear's current roughly 1,200 employees.
So Mr Montebourg needs a commitment from Titan before he tries to get the CGT to sit down with Goodyear.
The first step is for the CGT and Goodyear to reach an agreement on severance pay for all employees.
There will be no more employees in the factory.
Mr. Montebourg said you were prepared to guarantee those 333 jobs for four years.
Do you confirm that?
The only number I mentioned to the minister was 333.
I know he'd like a four-year warranty.
But as I said, the CGT and Goodyear must first agree on severance pay.
If all the employees agree, the plan to buy the factory starts with zero employees.
How can we guarantee a long-term job when there are no more employees left on site?
If Mr Montebourg can get the CGT and Goodyear to agree and Titan to buy the plant, we do intend to stay in Amiens-Nord for more than four years.
Bombardier's profit declined as aircraft deliveries and orders declined
Bombardier Inc, a Canadian aircraft and rail manufacturer, reported a 15 percent drop in net profit on Thursday, driven by a drop in third-quarter aircraft orders and deliveries and contract problems in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, has also not provided flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft or information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious schedule for commercial service before September.
After the first test flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, it flew only three times, and the question then arose whether the test phase was on track.
The results were not as expected and the share price fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, downgraded his rating on Thursday from  overperformance  to  sector performance  due to the low potential for the stock market to rise in the next quarter or two quarters.
 Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed with the profit margin in the Transportation division, said Cameron Doerksen in a note to customers.
We expect Bombardier to record new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight test program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical about the programme.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will catapult it into the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and first flew in September after months of delay.
But firm orders for the CSeries aircraft are modest so far at 177, and it appears that potential buyers are waiting for flight test results to validate the company's claims about the new airliner's energy efficiency and savings potential.
At present, the company has a total of 403 orders and purchase commitments from 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and CEO, is confident that Bombardier will reach its target of 300 firm orders before the first aircraft enters commercial service.
The leaders also reassured analysts and media on Thursday that the program was progressing on schedule.
 The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected, Beaudoin said in a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned during the time the aircraft was down.
Every builder plans differently.
We decided to make a first flight and schedule a period of updating, and that is what we did.
This will happen again throughout the flight program.
The second of the five test aircraft is scheduled to fly in the coming weeks, with the others to follow shortly after, the company said.
Yet analysts are skeptical that the first customer can fly a CSeries aircraft just 12 months after its maiden flight.
Bombardier said it was assessing the timing of entry into service and would provide further information in the coming months.
 This slowdown in flight testing  although it appears to be in line with Bombardier's internal schedule  reinforces our view that entry into service will be delayed to the first quarter of 2015, said Mr. Doerksen.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier's net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, a year earlier.
Adjusted earnings per share remained unchanged at 9 cents.
Revenues fell slightly from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts were expecting a 10 cent per share return and revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world's fourth largest aircraft manufacturer reported that it delivered 45 aircraft in the quarter, compared with 57 a year earlier.
Net orders fell to 26 aircraft, from 83 before.
