A report submitted to the European Commission in 2011 described intersex people as different from transsexual or transgender people, since their status is not related to sex but rather to their biological constitution, which is neither exclusively male nor exclusively female, but is generally both at the same time and not clearly defined as either.
These characteristics may manifest themselves in secondary sex characteristics, (such as muscle mass, hair, breast and height), primary sex characteristics (such as reproductive organs and sex organs), or chromosome structure and hormones.
