George Kerevan: The break-up of Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another disturbing story of independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland would have to join the European free movement area in order to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control at Berwick and a border of barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
While the Strathclyde newspaper did mention the possible economic benefits of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, it was not (and should not have been) in the headlines.
Nor did anyone say that EU Member States spend a lot of their time bypassing formal rules when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance would be a small concession that Brussels could offer in return for whatever it wants from the Scots.
So this is a story that is not a story.
And a story so old that it's now frozen: I first heard the rumour that  independence means passport control  over 40 years ago.
Yet an interesting point has been overlooked in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe's instructions, anyway?
Why trade the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
The real news about Europe is this: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally come to a standstill.
With the euro crisis, the Europe Project is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposed to the EU or advocating for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming out of nowhere, won almost five million votes in the September federal elections and ousted the Liberal Democrat Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the lock on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many to think that the Europe Project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits  this was only true for Greece.
The European system has instead imposed on its members exchange rates favourable to German exporters  which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the national currency, the countries of southern Europe are left with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make the big cuts in wages and public spending encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current budgetary and monetary problems, there is a deeper productivity malaise in Europe.
Following the  green  energy policies imposed by Brussels  which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer  European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the US.
This is a costly disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt rages, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the struggling French economy to grapple.
The result: Marine Le Pen's far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the Socialists to power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote  a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split from the right will automatically favour the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among the white French working class?
It wants to use the European elections next year to create a single anti-monetary and anti-European bloc in the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties win this election, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
I think that very soon anti-European sentiment and anti-monetary sentiment in Europe will unite and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something more like the Europe of the (sovereign) nations, the free Europe favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will have their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will turn a blind eye to the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of Little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending Berlin and Brussels for a walk.
I believe that Scotland could accommodate a freer European agreement provided we kept our own currency.
Cooperation with other countries with similar views would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
Otherwise we should follow Norway's example and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is  and it should be noted  the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, having won a dramatic majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition that followed.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to vote for independence now if it is to accept austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty - Aging early
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is imminent
There's no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe the obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The tendency toward premature puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a pediatric endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new norm.
 I spend a lot of time reassuring parents  generally, this does not indicate a rapid progression towards full puberty , Kaplowitz said.
The obvious signs of development, such as breast budding, underarm and pubic hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight increase in the age of first menstruation in the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is now 12 and a half years, up from 12 years in 1970.
 Once the breasts have begun to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first menstrual periods appear, says Kaplowitz, who also wrote Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test for how puberty will progress.
There is debate as to what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered to be early  when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, the development slows down or stops  this is something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
A faster course may warrant tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature bone aging that can slow growth and shrink in adulthood.
Recommendations for medication and hormone therapy are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication but acknowledges that  controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others .
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young daughters to have their period.
 They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues, Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock", recalls a mother whose daughter had her first period when she was 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset about being first among her friends.
There are many popular theories about the causes of premature puberty.
Yet, there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or the sexual messages in the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is that there is an obesity epidemic.
He was part of a study of girls aged 6 to 9 that linked body fat percentage to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In that country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Worldwide, the mechanisms of premature puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have facial hair and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency toward true early puberty is not as pronounced as it is in girls.
Other physicians attending the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the subject.
Acne and pubic hair are common, even in infants and toddlers.
 We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty, said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
 This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected, explained Kaplowitz.
If you remain calm, your child will generally respond well.
Girls who are in early puberty need to be reassured that even if it happens sooner than expected, it is a normal part of life.
A tribute to the Coen Brothers folk
"Inside Llewyn Davis" by the Coen brothers, winner of the last Cannes Film Festival, is a nostalgic, funny film about the Greenwich Village of 1961 and the folk music that was just beginning to resonate there, before Bob Dylan arrived.
Joel and Ethan Coen, whose filmography has just been shown at the Cinémathèque française, won the Palme d'Or at Cannes in 1991 for Barton Fink.
When they couldn't hire Dylan or the trio Peter, Paul and Mary, Joel and Ethan Coen turned their attention to rising American movie star Oscar Isaac, 33, and also to global pop star Justin Timberlake.
In this humorous film where music is the central character and songs performed live, Oscar Isaac reveals himself to be an accomplished folk musician and singer, while Timberlake, his friend in the film, leaves pop for folk music with an infectious jubilation.
As for Carey Mulligan, she's moved from the rich outfits of Daisy Mulligan in "The Magnificent Gatsby" to less shiny clothes, a soft voice when she sings, but the machine gun-shot swear word when she speaks.
"Inside Llewyn Davis" is about a week of tribulations for a folk singer who can't break through and gets angry at the whole world.
He's willing to back down on the replacements in the studios.
He's homeless, he's just going around the couches of his friends who still want to see him.
A documentary air
"His relationship with success is tortured, that's what we were interested in: a mix of bad luck, a guy who's not there at the right time, who's not career-oriented but who's honest, with self-destructive behavior", Ethan Coen, who won several Oscars and awards at Cannes with his brother Joel, told the press.
If Llewyn Davis did not exist, the two folk music fans based their story on real figures of the time like folk musician Dave Von Ronk.
The idea was to show the moment before the arrival of Greenwich Village, a New York neighborhood destined to become "the epicenter of the folk music boom that would spawn international stars", as Van Ronk's friend Elijah Wald wrote.
The film then takes on the look of a documentary, from the dusty music label filled with unsold 33T's inhabited by an old, unpaid secretary, to the musical choices of the studios and cafes where the singers performed.
The Coen brothers' magic still works with a funny character that runs through the film all the time: a beautiful, sparkly-eyed red cat, Llewyn Davis' lucky companion.
When asked how he came up with his character, actor and singer Justin Timberlake recalled growing up in Tennessee, "bathed in blues and country".
