Gérard de Villiers, the author of "SAS", is dead.
He's never heard of retirement.
French publishing phenomenon, Gérard de Villiers, who died on Thursday at the age of 83, had just published his 200th SAS, "The Revenge of the Kremlin".
In February, The New York Times hailed him as "the spy novelist who knew too much".
He had just spent ten days in Afghanistan, the setting for the 198th and 199th installments of the famous series of spy novels.
Physically disabled by a very serious heart attack in December 2010, he was traveling with a walker during this trip.
And before Afghanistan, he also went back to Libya, Russia, Lebanon and Mali.
With four SASs published a year, Gérard de Villiers, born on 8 December 1929 in Paris, claimed to be unaware of the exact number of books sold since 1965 and the publication of "SAS in Istanbul", the first in the series, almost half a century ago.
"Probably between 120 and 150 million in all countries combined", he said last March.
His Burmese cat on his lap, in the living room of his huge apartment building on Foch Avenue, a few steps from the Arc de Triomphe, the evil eye under his white hair, he quoted some of the languages into which the adventures of the SAS were translated: Italian, German, Russian, Greek, Japanese or Korean.
"Not counting pirate editions", he added, pointing to a pile of books on the coffee table among the bronzes or ivory brought from the 130 countries surveyed to place his novels.
For the price of a pack of cigarettes, the reader is entitled to the traditional cover with the picture of a young woman with a good chest, carrying a pistol or assault rifle.
Inside, His Serene Highness (SAS) Prince Malko Linge, a penniless Austrian aristocrat and CIA contractor to pay for the repairs to the family castle, sets out to hunt down all the bad guys on earth, communists in the 1970s and 1980s, then jihadists from the 1990s onwards.
Each book has the same recipe: a lot of geopolitics and exoticism, some hardcore sex, a hint of violence and torture.
"I never pretended to be a literary writer", explained Gérard de Villiers.
I think of myself as a storyteller who writes to distract people I don't text.
He worked "like the great prewar reporters, the Albert London type, who went there and came back with real, long investigations".
The SAS father said, "Make some kind of geopolitical soap opera".
"I always follow my files (Afghanistan, Syria, ...) before I leave", added Gérard de Villiers.
There I meet journalists, including those from AFP, diplomats, people from the intelligence services whom I have known for some 20 or 30 years.
As a result, many of his SAS are often prescient: for example, a month before the attack on a Syrian regime command center that killed several senior officials, he told the story in "The Road to Damascus".
In "The Madmen of Benghazi", he was the first to reveal the existence of a secret CIA command center in that city, the birthplace of the Libyan uprising.
In 1980, he staged the assassination of Egyptian President Anwar Sadat in "The Cairo Plot", a year before the bombing.
In October 2012, in "Panic in Bamako", he reported on the jihadist 4X4 columns that were founding in the Malian capital.
I am not a fortune teller, defended Gérard de Villiers, I simply make assumptions from countries I know well and, from time to time, some of my assumptions come true.
After these trips to often troubled areas, he would sit for a month behind his IBM daisy typewriter from 1976 "whose parts had all been changed".
300 pages later, he would write the word "FIN" and correct each page with a pen.
On the walls of his office are AK-47 assault rifles, erotic photos and photos of the author with African warlords.
Regularly accused of being a sexist by feminist leagues and of racism by human rights organizations, Gérard de Villiers dismissed these accusations in two sentences.
Some women are sexual objects in my books, but others are beautiful, intelligent, brave women.
I am always welcomed in Africa, where I have many readers.
Gérard de Villiers said it: "Malko Linge, like all heroes, has no age".
He's not going to die or retire.
No more than I do.
Aircraft manufacturers are fighting over seat width as big orders are at stake
The dispute rages among major aircraft manufacturers over the width of passenger seats on long-haul flights, paving the way for a bitter confrontation at the Dubai Airshow this month.
The dispute concerns the width of seats offered on long-haul flights to economy class passengers  who are not always the most sought after by airlines, but for whom the space allocated is essential to increase efficiency gains in the latest aircraft introduced by Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
This week, Airbus called on the airline industry to set a standard for a seat size of at least 18 inches (45.72 cm) in economy class, but its big US rival Boeing says it should be up to the airlines to decide.
The dispute erupted as aircraft manufacturers look to sell even larger versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft, hoping for a record number of orders at the event from November 17-21.
The way the seats will be arranged in the rear of the aircraft  in particular, whether there will be 9 or 10 front seats  is essential to the economic performance of the  mini-jumbo  segment.
Boeing says its redesigned  777X  will be able to seat 406 people in economy class in seats over 17 inches wide, and will be configured with 10 seats per row.
Airbus says the competing version of its A350 will carry 350 people in economy class in 18-inch wide seats configured in rows of 9.
The giants of the aviation industry often exchange blows on technical matters by advertising in the professional press.
Today, Airbus is making a direct appeal to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to take the lead with over 100 orders.
We recently saw what could be the beginning of a new advertising war with the presentation to the financiers of a photo showing three people fighting each other in a restaurant, titled Would You Take This?
 Boeing offers long-haul flights in smaller seats than in regional turboprop aircraft, said John Leahy, commercial director of Airbus.
As eating habits change, people get fatter, but the seats on planes haven't changed dramatically.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 became the defining jet of modern long-haul travel, and the turn of the century, the average American between the ages of 40 and 49 gained 10 percent more weight, according to U.S. Department of Health and Human Services data.
The average American in the 21st century is 39.7 inches tall, according to U.S. health statistics.
Airbus says its rival is clinging to a seat concept dating back to the 1950s, when the newly named  jet set  aircraft's circumference was narrower.
Airbus adds that it commissioned a study that shows that an extra inch in seat width would improve sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus' figures for seat width and says it is not for manufacturers to decide how airlines balance the price of tickets and equipment.
He also says the study shows that the cabin experience is not just dependent on seat width.
 It's really about giving airlines flexibility and allowing them to do what they think they need to do to run their business , said Kent Craver, Boeing's passenger satisfaction manager.
They don't want to be told what will make them profitable.
They know their business better than anyone.
For passengers, it is more about having some freedom of movement, but for suppliers, it is increasingly an issue that could affect their results.
The dispute is being driven by a race for orders for aircraft worth an estimated $700 billion or more at market prices in the coming decades, enough to tip the balance of US and European exports.
As Reuters first reported in July, the configuration of the seats is exactly what fuels the battle between the latest aircraft.
Airbus and Boeing both claim a seat efficiency in their latest long-haul twin engine models 20% higher than that of the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 777-300ER.
Boeing's performance is based in part on comparison between the 777X configured with 10 rows of seats and the original 777 model configured with 9 rows.
The unit cost savings are small compared to the aircraft configured with 10 seats per row currently in service.
 Boeing is doing this to accommodate more seats and make its aircraft more competitive by comparing our products, said Kevin Keniston, Director of Passenger Comfort at European aircraft manufacturer Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say that the cabins configured with 10 seats per row in the existing 777s suggest that many passengers are in favor of a denser configuration, which can go hand in hand with cheaper fares.
 An 18-inch seat width would be perfect for passengers, but the reality is that from a commercial standpoint, Airbus' proposal is motivated by the 777's threat, said cabin interior expert Mary Kirby, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not provide seats but offer a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The aircraft dealers who travel the world carry even a meter with them to check the competing configurations.
While they pride themselves on offering comfortable aircraft, all manufacturers also offer aircraft with high-density configurations to low-cost airlines and for regional travel.
Airbus offers an A350 configured with 10 seats per row but says it has not yet sold it.
Until recently, Airbus emphasised the need for greater customization of cabins by offering wider aisle-side seats on some of its aircraft.
Without the support of the only other major manufacturer of large modern aircraft, experts say its call to the airline industry for a standard size for seats is unlikely to succeed, but it could make the 777X's sales surge go away.
