New nicotine vaccine could take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed a vaccine against nicotine that could take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from lifelong nicotine addiction.
More tests are needed before human trials can begin, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial signs were encouraging.
 We really hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can help millions of smokers who have tried to quit, exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but find that their addiction is strong enough to overcome these different approaches, said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to carry the genetic information needed to design anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady flow of antibodies.
The antibodies track down all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting his or her dose of nicotine.
In tests, vaccinated mice that were then given nicotine continued their normal activity.
But the mice that were not vaccinated were calmed down, the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have proven ineffective because they contain antibodies.
The injections had to be repeated so frequently to keep antibody levels high that they were too expensive and impractical.
But the new vaccine should be much cheaper because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future vaccine for human use were completely safe, it could be given to children before they are tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing any addiction to nicotine.
But it's more likely to be used by smokers who want to quit.
 They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and this may help them to quit their bad habit, he added.
British scientists said the results were interesting but that much more research was needed.
