FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on board planes (but not make a call with their mobile phone)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices door-to-door to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music  but not talk on their mobile phones  under the highly anticipated new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect changes immediately.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from one airline to another, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the crew training manuals and the rules on aircraft storage to comply.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue are among the airlines that have already submitted plans.
 Depending on the plan, we may approve an expanded use of electronic devices very soon, the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the doors of the aircraft are closed.
They're not supposed to turn them back on until the plane reaches 10,000 feet and the captain gives the go-ahead.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices when descending from the aircraft before landing and not to turn them on again until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during takeoff, landing and grounding, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was happy about these changes.
 Once the new policy is safely implemented  and we will work closely with carriers for this  it will be beneficial to everyone , Glading explained in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like  hall overseers  when it comes to this issue.
But it will still be forbidden to connect to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and text messages or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be required to turn their smartphones, tablets and other devices into airplane mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble-style online game that actor Alec Baldwin was playing on his smartphone in 2011 when he was nobly ejected from an American Airlines flight after refusing to turn off his device while the device was parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will always need to be put away because they could hurt someone if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be prohibited.
The regulatory authority for cell phones belongs to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert on CBS News, said that cell phones were still considered a risk.
 Cell phones are a real problem, not only because they could potentially interfere with navigation instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile phone relay antennas if used on board , Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the issue recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
Pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to relax restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid safety reason for these bans.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one third of passengers forget to turn off their mobile devices or do so deliberately.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers carried FM radios, the then high-tech gadget.
The new airliners rely much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and are FAA approved.
Airlines have been allowing their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Airplanes modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow for wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much lower power radio transmissions than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal transmissions when you turn a page.
But the transmissions are stronger when the devices are downloading or sending data.
Amazon.com is among those pushing for easing of restrictions on passengers' use of electronic devices.
In 2011, company executives loaded a commercial airliner with Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This has inspired mixed feelings among the members of the FAA advisory committee about whether or not the use of the aircraft poses a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed the interference from the aircraft was real, even though the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only anecdotal reports from pilots that the devices could interfere with an aircraft's systems, and most of them were very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
A group in the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling them common sense arrangements for technology-enabled travelers.
 We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not incompatible with safety , said Roger Dow, President and CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
