Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing business together and defining what wealth and job creators want to see changed in our relationship with the EU.
To do this, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders and asked them what they thought of Britain, business and the EU.
YouGov surveyed over 1000 business leaders, broadly representative of all business sizes, sectors and regions in Britain.
The findings of the survey will surprise many.
We found that the vast majority of companies now seek to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and developing while EU states are stagnating.
They want the government to prioritize new trade links with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than getting bogged down in the long and arduous process of reforming the European institutional arcana.
When asked for their views on specific policy issues  ranging from monopoly regulation to product laws  most business leaders believe that control of these key competences should revert to Westminster.
The single market has caused widespread discontent, with businesses saying that the cost of the Brussels regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trading area  40% of large, traditionally more pro-European companies even agree.
Finally, and even more tellingly, our survey of business leaders found that a large majority wanted Britain to continue its efforts to change the Treaty and develop a relationship with the EU based on trade rather than politics.
This finding, which is found in all large groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the business world is pushing for  meaningful change  that will put the UK back on its feet.
The stakes are high  succeeding in changing the Treaty and better representing Britain's interests would see a swing of 16% in the vote in favour of the country remaining in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should not have any doubt: this survey shows that British businesses support this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain's EU membership.
It also shows that companies hope that the renegotiation will be a significant shift in the current balance of power in favour of a return to UK hands.
It is possible and increasingly necessary to better represent the interests of British businesses as the euro area moves towards a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in Britain and, as the findings of our survey show, for businesses this means refocusing on trade and a fundamental change in the regulatory approach in Brussels.
