How biometrics will invade our lives
No more passwords to enter to access her smartphone or pay for her groceries?
Researchers in the United States, France and Japan predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors on phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a transversal and transnational universe such as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this craze for biometrics, but are concerned.
In 2011 alone, the French National Commission for Information and Freedom authorized 774 fingerprint, hand shape or hand vein recognition systems in companies, government, canteens, etc.
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere, anytime", says Justin Brookman, director of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington, D.C.
What is the reason for such optimism in some and pessimism in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most commonly used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the vein network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
"For example, some concrete workers have severely damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible", says Philippe Robin, technical director of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection and checking of the vein network and the contour of the hand requires a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a safety feature - you cannot capture this data without them knowing - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted over the past 20 years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
With the increased accuracy of sensors and the computing power of computers needed for data analysis, these techniques are becoming operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold in the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture's R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automated border crossings using facial recognition.
Now it's possible to identify a face or an iris in motion.
"Today we are doing research on voice recognition or walking with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment", says Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
The unique and unmistakable marker DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data", confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospects at the CNIL.
But DNA testing is still very time-consuming and very expensive.
NEC offers the police a suitcase that costs 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at a crime scene in an hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognizing a person from among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
Identification has so far been about issuing identity papers: biometric data (fingerprints, photographs, iris) must be compared with the information the State has on all citizens already registered.
This helps to ensure that a person is not trying to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison can have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or shop.
"We retrieve the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them with the photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet", explains Dany Nassif, who is responsible for commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other uses include taking pictures of a quidam in line at a store, tracking its progress with facial recognition, and calculating waiting times.
Authentication was initially concerned with physical access (frontier, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, attendance control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of a friend pointing for another", explains Cyrille Bataller of Accenture.
But increasingly, authentication will also include transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some ATMs by inserting your card and placing your hand on a biometric reader.
A similar technique is being tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in a store with a credit card, the customer does not type in a code, but inserts his finger into a scanner that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon be available to French traders.
Ways to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If a customer stays in the checkout room for 30 seconds less because of biometrics, that's great", says the manager of a large store.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
Finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which locks if you try to move it", says Philippe Robin of Thales.
But because of the lack of detailed studies, it is impossible to know whether these discourses really convince users.
Privacy experts, on the other hand, continue to be concerned.
"The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the enormous amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr and Picasa make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance", predicts Andrew Patrick of the Privacy Commissioner's Office in Canada.
