Scientists have recently discovered how the movements of a dog's tail are linked to its mood.
Previous studies have found that happy dogs wag their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wagged their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said:  Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in the stimuli that trigger positive or negative emotions. 
Here we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that just as in humans, the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa in dogs, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotion.
To learn more about how dogs react to other dogs' disordered tail movements, researchers followed animals as they watched movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals' heart rates and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not be long before we understand why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained:  We showed dogs films that featured other dogs  either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion  and we were able to manipulate the movement of the tail and present it as going more to the left or right. 
When the animals saw a dog without expression wagging its tail to the right (from the dog's point of view), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they saw a tail that was veering mostly to the left (again from the dog's point of view wagging its tail), their heart rate sped up and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs deliberately communicated with one another through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not be concerned about.
He added:  If you encounter other dogs repeatedly and notice that most of the time, moving their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience.
The researchers say the findings could help pet owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their pets' emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Science at Bristol University, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right handedness in a dog.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog and to the right when they look at a happy dog.
And in another scientific study done by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said:  Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than the right, instead of becoming anxious  the opposite of what was shown in the Italian study. 
He suggested that the differences might be due to the fact that the dogs in the different studies did not fully view the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he said.
 Although there is a lot of evidence from different mammals that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are still to be clarified  and dogs are no exception , he said.
However, given how easily their behavior can be recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why their tails sometimes move to one side and sometimes to the other.
