The cry of despair from an Obama voter
I voted twice for President Obama, believing in the possibility of change.
He says Obama has made commendable efforts thwarted by Republican Party obstructionism.
Obstructionism does not excuse the problems with the Obamacare website, nor the drone attacks.
The memory of Obama's 2008 campaign is a sad reminder of what could have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading a horribly sad book these days.
It's a book I thought would encourage me through the gloom of my second year of medicine and give me hope again.
It's called  The Audacity to Win  and it's a memoir of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patients' medical records at night and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and speeches could take your breath away.
The election ended in a landslide victory and news anchors took time to reflect on the historical nature of the moment.
My classmates wept for joy, and my parents kept all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was marching on the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama's transition period before he took office in 2008, he had 82 percent favorable opinions.
And then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a difficult awakening, it's like coming out of a dream.
It's hard to remember those optimistic days, they're like distant memories, a sad reminder of past opportunities.
The change really happened in the years since I first voted.
It was nothing like I imagined.
I credit Obama with great achievements, from passing the Affordable Care Act to pulling our military out of Iraq, to ending the "never seen nor heard" and killing Osama bin Laden.
Furthermore, I believe partisan obstructionism has destroyed too many efforts to move our nation forward in immigration reform, public health care, and closing Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending the Obama administration in front of my peers and colleagues, I can no longer provide an explanation.
I'm on the verge of political despair.
Republican obstruction cannot explain the wiretapping of foreign leaders, or drone attacks on innocent foreign children.
It cannot explain the National Security Agency's collection of data on Americans' private lives, or the prosecution of whistleblowers who expose government wrongdoing.
It cannot justify the murder of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without trial, or the evasion of public funds and the overspending of authorized presidential campaigns.
It cannot justify the conclusions of a report that says the White House's efforts to silence the media are the most aggressive since the Nixon administration.
And, more recently, it can't excuse not being able to design a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if this is what I expected.
If, at 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Of course, the election function is unpredictable, because the opposition political party and random events, like the massacre of Newton, influence our public conversation.
However, all the examples I have listed above seem to be largely the choice of the administration.
That's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confused and unrefined alternative that did not seem to determine his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected to a second term, free from the pressure of future elections, would keep the promises we'd heard about for so long.
Yet while the positive opinion index has plunged below 45% this week, it is even more difficult to go back to 2008 through this book.
It makes me long for the many promises that have been swept away.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Obama suffered huge losses to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
At a meeting after the campaign, he told his team that they needed to get back on track and stay loyal to their cause.
