Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents her two new group choreographies at Danse Danse: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies by Satie.
An evening that shows the whole of Chouinard's prism, from art to tics and from black to white.
A white screen serves as the back wall.
On the white carpet in the vast space of the Maisonneuve, a body, thin as a line and dressed in black, advances.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, a simple trait, takes shape.
And this will be the shape of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, all dressed in black, only their hands and faces uncovered, wait on either side of the playing field, rush in when the next graph appears, embody it, run out.
This black and white play by Henri Michaux is performed in solo relay, in unison group (a mass that does solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
We think of "Glory of the Morning", where, as a soloist, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on signs, placed in a line in the foreground.
It's the same principle, but a giant PowerPoint version.
The music is loud here, drums and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the rhythm is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monochord and monotone in the cry, and continues dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to go back.
This loud, energetic, if long, discharge eventually deafens and numbs.
So does the regularity of visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - image creation has always been a strength in Chouinard - like those hair that blur or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
It seems that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has won with her tics.
The result: the bodies look flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux's inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider and more glib imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the ending, in the negative, with its dancers chopped by strobe light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches on the magic.
The audience loved it, the reception was warm.
Gymnastics, after the interchange, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in gray, the dancers and the piano are covered with cloth, like furniture in an abandoned house.
On the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their musical clumsiness, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, couples perform in love duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transitional solos, moving ensembles, choirs, the writing is less binary.
Clowns, also familiar to Chouinard, show off their red noses in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Love is either a butcher, a fugitive or a gambler.
The gestures, the laughter and the little screams beautifully translate the archaic, grace and ridicule of coitus bodies, of the beings that merge.
But the play takes off after the rescue.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the dancers shuffle, descend among the spectators, glow, smoke, short circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness are sweating, and it is Chouinard's art here to contaminate the public.
