Vote here or on your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of the Year 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the 10 other heroes, to be voted CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue their extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate between periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and visit hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, causing a hematoma that would plague him for the rest of his life.
 There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon, said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, getting him any treatment he could get.
 It is not easy, adds Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5:00, rush to the hospital to be first, and you're not first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation hasn't changed much since Dr Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In comparison, the United States has 1 doctor for every 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not afford the consultation.
Two out of every five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three-quarters of the country's health expenditure is in the private sector.
 The only problem they have is poverty, explained Dr Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they can't enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed over 700 free surgeries in the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he created a nonprofit humanitarian organization, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, about 30 people, having attached the medical equipment to the roof, crowd into vans and cross difficult terrain to reach the villages where help is most needed.
Luck doesn't always follow them.
They had to push the vehicles over muddy roads and rivers many times.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as heroes: the community throws a party, sings and dances, and offers them the best accommodations available.
In these villages, free healthcare is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr Bwelle  with his big smile and energy  is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team starts seeing hundreds of patients.
 We receive 500 people at each visit, Bwelle said.
Sometimes they live 60 kilometers from the village, and they walk.
This traveling hospital provides a variety of health care services.
Many people are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, collected glasses or a free birth certificate  a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford it.
In the evening, the team practices simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually performed in a school, town hall, or home; after the procedure, the patient stands up and goes to the recovery room to give his place to the next person.
By using the lighting of the generator, the operating room, and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a tiring pace, but the musicians in the villages usually help the team stay motivated.
 They beat drums all night to keep us awake so we can continue working , Bwelle explained.
On Sunday, the team returns to town tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 free surgeries last year, and they know that their presence can make a difference for those they help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would enable him to work again.
 This will change my future and that of my family, said the man.
In addition to running this traveling hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
He explains that this second job is where 60 per cent of his association's funding comes from; the rest is covered by private donations.
 I don't know when he sleeps , said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's still in the hospital or trying to raise money for his association so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Bwelle on his missions, it's a field-learning opportunity they don't have at home.
 We were able to participate in operations to help with blood sponging or to get the instruments through to Dr Bwelle , Ms O'Malley explained.
It's not something you get to do in America when you're a second-year medical student.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, and often arrive with medical supplies collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their boarding, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
 He is a hero, there is no doubt , said Katie O'Malley.
He gave his life for this association, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is not about to die.
For Dr Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others to live happy lives in fulfillment of the promise he made to his father is something that brings him great joy.
 I am so happy when I do this job, added Bwelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons I do this.
