French police will arrest Anderlecht fans who come with other than RSCA buses
The French police have decided to impose strict rules regarding the match between the Royal Sporting Club of Anderlecht and Paris Saint-Germain scheduled for Tuesday, Marie Verbeke, spokeswoman for the Brussels-Midday police area, said on Friday.
Belgian RSCA fans who wish to attend this Champions League match will have to use the travel system put in place by the RSCA.
"The bus convoy will be escorted by police from a former border post in Rekem to the PSG stadium", the spokeswoman said.
The process will be the same on the way back.
"If other supporters were planning to travel to Paris by other means, the French police prefecture has informed that measures have been taken to allow for arrests and even guards in sight", Marie Verbeke said.
Living together in French: the challenge of the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board
At the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board, 62% of pupils have a mother tongue other than French.
This prompted a year ago a consultation with parents, pupils, teachers and education staff to consider ways of better integrating students who live in cross-cultural situations.
The school board has just unveiled its vision of "Living together in French".
The organisation Vision diversité has been walking through schools for a year to help students of all backgrounds discover common ground that is not limited to the French language.
The discovery of neighborhoods, our architecture, our places are landmarks.
Great names of writers, artists, whether they were native or foreign.
Who are our builders?
"So we design projects so that they can relate to all this", explains Aïda Kamar, president of Vision Diversity.
Michel Venne of the New World Institute identified several challenges for the school board.
"For example, the transmission of Québec culture, the sense of belonging, the support of staff in the changes that are taking place among the student clientele", he says.
The Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board has set up a research centre to provide teachers with tools, who sometimes come from elsewhere.
Rachida Azdouz, from the University of Montreal, will be the scientific director.
Preparation to manage a class in a North American, Quebec context.
"Different teaching strategies are the real need", she sums up.
Research will focus on inclusion from all angles: linguistic, educational, social and cultural.
